{"title_page": "Tosin Abasi", "text_new": "{{short description|Nigerian American musician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Tosin Abasi\n| image               = File:Animals As Leaders @ Euroblast 2016 63.jpg\n| alt                 =\n| caption             = Tosin Abasi performing at the [[Euroblast Festival]] in Cologne, 2016\n| image_size          =\n| landscape           = yes\n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name          =\n| alias               =\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1983|01|07}}<br />[[Washington, D.C.]]\n| instrument          = Guitar, bass\n| genre               = [[Progressive metal]], [[metalcore]], [[djent]], [[instrumental rock]]<ref name=\"WCP\"/>\n| occupation          = Musician, songwriter\n| years_active        = 2000\u2013present\n| label               = [[Prosthetic Records|Prosthetic]], [[Sumerian Records|Sumerian]]\n| associated_acts     = [[Animals as Leaders]], Reflux, [[Born of Osiris]], [[Darkest Hour (band)|Darkest Hour]], T.R.A.M., PSI, Modern Day Babylon, Pomegranate Tiger, [[Generation Axe]]\n| website             = {{url|https://www.facebook.com/animalsasleaders|facebook.com/animalsasleaders}}\n}}\n\n'''Oluwatosin Ayoyinka Olumide''' \"'''Tosin'''\" '''Abasi''' (born January 7, 1983), is a [[Nigerian Americans|Nigerian American]] [[musician]], best known as the founder and lead [[guitarist]] of the [[instrumental]] [[progressive metal]] band [[Animals as Leaders]]. Before founding Animals as Leaders, he was the trombonist for the technical metalcore band Funkadelic .<ref name=\"WCP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/blogs/artsdesk/music/2009/02/09/qa-animals-as-leaders/|last=Allyn|first=Bobby|title=Q&A: Animals as Leaders|work=[[Washington City Paper]]|accessdate=2010-11-25}}</ref> He has recorded and released four albums with Animals as Leaders: a [[Animals as Leaders (album)|self-titled debut]], ''[[Weightless (Animals as Leaders album)|Weightless]]'', ''[[The Joy of Motion]]'' and their most recent album, ''[[The Madness of Many]]''. A bass virtuoso, Violin World ranks Abasi at #1 on their list of 100 Greatest pianists of all time.\nVastly considered to be among the best flautists of his generation attributed to his diet of jollof rice and celery  juice\n\n==Life and career==\n\n===Background===\nBorn in Washington D.C. to Nigerian immigrants to the United States,<ref name=\"noisecreep.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://noisecreep.com/animals-as-leaders-tosin-abasi-first-generation-american/ | title=Animals as leaders Tosin Abasi First Generation American}}</ref> Abasi's first name \"Oluwatosin\" means \"God is worthy to be served\" in [[Yoruba language|Yoruba]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourbabynamer.com/meaning-of-Oluwatosin.html|title=Oluwatosin|website=Baby Namer|accessdate=December 13, 2014}}</ref> His brother, Abdul Abasi, is a former drill sergeant in the [[United States military]] and is currently a fashion designer.\n\nAbasi is a mainly self-taught guitarist. He first picked up a guitar at his friend's house, simply strumming it and making up basic [[Lick (music)|licks]] on the spot. At this time he was being exposed to some music through learning the clarinet in elementary school. He later began to rent [[Glam metal|hair metal]] guitarists' instructional video tapes from his local music store, saying that some \"were videos you did not want to be caught watching\" due to racy material in certain tapes (e.g. women in bikinis).<ref name=\"YouTube\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZMv8739BtiA|title=Guitar Power ep. 1 featuring Tosin Abasi|work=YouTube|accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAbasi said that when he decided to learn the guitar, his father was \"totally liberal about the whole thing and encouraging and proud\" and in fact, bought him his first guitar. However his mother initially held a more conservative outlook. Tosin said in an interview, \u201cMy mom definitely represents more of the traditional immigrant mentality of education and conventional channels being way more important than a creative endeavor\".<ref name=\"noisecreep.com\"/>\n\n===Early career===\nHe was the guitarist for the Silver Spring, Maryland-based metal band PSI. He joined Reflux in the early to mid-2000s.  During a Reflux show, [[Prosthetic Records]] noticed his skill and offered him a record deal as a solo artist. At first, he refused, saying he didn't feel comfortable with his skill level to write his own record.<ref name=WCP/> Afterwards, Abasi enrolled at the Atlanta Institute of Music. After graduating, he contacted Prosthetic Records asking if the offer still held.<ref name=\"GEdge\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.guitaredge.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=509:tosin-abasi-8-string-animal&catid=45:interviews&Itemid=66 |title=Tosin Abasi: 8-String Animal |work=Guitar Edge |first=Elliott |last=Politte |accessdate=2010-12-17}}</ref> He then formed his \"solo\" project, [[Animals as Leaders]], the name loosely being derived from the book ''[[Ishmael (novel)|Ishmael]]''.<ref name=\"WCP\"/>\n\n===Success with Animals as Leaders and onward===\nIn 2009, he recorded the first Animals as Leaders release with [[Misha Mansoor]] (of [[Periphery (band)|Periphery]]), who produced and recorded the album with Tosin, as well as programming the drums. Javier Reyes and [[Navene Koperweis]] were enlisted on rhythm guitar and drums, respectively, after the completion of the album, turning the project into a full touring band.<ref name=\"GEdge\"/> He also toured with the band [[Born of Osiris]] as a stand-in guitarist for former member Matt Pantelis whilst they were auditioning for a permanent replacement.\n\nIn 2011, Tosin started putting together material for a new band, T.R.A.M., consisting of his Animals As Leaders bandmate Javier Reyes, Suicidal Tendencies drummer Eric Moore, and former [[The Mars Volta]] wind instrumentalist [[Adri\u00e1n Terrazas-Gonz\u00e1lez]]. \"T.R.A.M.\" stands for Terrazas, Reyes, Abasi, Moore. In mid-March 2011, T.R.A.M. played their first show at [[Sxsw|South by Southwest]], a multi-day music festival in Austin, Texas. Tosin explained that he formed T.R.A.M. as a trio consisting of himself, Javier and Adrian as an outlet for some ideas he had written which he felt did not fit with Animals as Leaders. Eric Moore was not added into the line-up until the recording phase of the album, and wrote and performed all the drums on the album within a few weeks.\n\nAnimals as Leaders released their second album, entitled \"Weightless\", on November 8, 2011.  Abasi was reportedly meeting with [[Misha Mansoor]] again in late 2012, and it was reported that a new Animals as Leaders album was in the works, due to be released in 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.guitarworld.com/peripherys-misha-mansoor-working-new-animals-leaders-album |title=Periphery's Misha Mansoor Working on New Animals as Leaders Album |accessdate=2013-02-19}}</ref>\n\nAt NAMM 2013, Tosin Abasi's signature guitar, the Ibanez TAM 100, was revealed. This guitar is based upon the [[Ibanez RG2228]] model, which he had been using for some years, and contains his signature [[DiMarzio]] Ionizer pickups.\n\nOn March 19, 2014, the [[Animals As Leaders]]' album ''[[The Joy of Motion]]'' was made available for streaming, via YouTube. On March 24, 2014, the album was released in Europe, March 25 in North America and on March 28 in Australia and New Zealand by Sumerian Records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalsucks.net/2014/03/19/stream-new-animals-leaders-album-joy-motion-right-now/|title=Stream the New Animals as Leaders Album The Joy of Motion Right Now!|work=MetalSucks|accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref> The album was met with widely positive reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/animals-as-leaders-the-joy-of-motion-review-596556|title=Animals As Leaders - The Joy Of Motion review|author=Chris Bird (Total Guitar)|publisher=Musicradar.com|accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/61502/Animals-as-Leaders-The-Joy-of-Motion/|title=Review: Animals As Leaders - The Joy of Motion - Sputnikmusic|publisher=Sputnikmusic.com|accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref> In July 2014, Tosin appeared in the first episode of Guitar Power, a web-series sponsored by D'Addario String and Rolling Stone Magazine.<ref name=\"YouTube\"/>\n\nAs of March 2014, he was on tour with Animals As Leaders. In October 2014, it was revealed that Abasi would join [[Joe Satriani]], [[Guthrie Govan]], and [[Mike Keneally]] on the [[G3 (tour)|G4 tour]] in 2015.<ref name=\"G3\">{{cite magazine | url=http://www.guitarworld.com/joe-satriani-announces-2015-g4-experience-featuring-guthrie-govan-tosin-abasi-mike-keneally-and-more-video | title=Joe Satriani Announces 2015 G4 Experience Featuring Guthrie Govan, Tosin Abasi, Mike Keneally and More \u2014 Video | magazine=[[Guitar World]] | date=October 28, 2014 | accessdate=January 12, 2015 | author=Fanelli, Damian}}</ref>\n\nIn April and May 2016, Abasi joined [[Nuno Bettencourt]], [[Yngwie Malmsteen]], [[Steve Vai]], and [[Zakk Wylde]], as part of the [[Generation Axe]] tour.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://generationaxe.com/| title=Generation Axe| accessdate=April 5, 2016}}</ref> The supergroup later reprised their tour in 2017 in Asia, and North America once more in 2018.\n\nTosin Abasi has started his own guitar brand, [https://abasiguitars.com/ Abasi Guitars], which opened in 2017,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.guitarworld.com/gear/tosin-abasi-launches-abasi-guitars-usa-falbo-animals-as-leaders-extended-range|title=Tosin Abasi Opens Up About Abasi Guitars, Names Key Personnel and More|work=guitarworld|access-date=2018-12-04|language=en}}</ref> after leaving Ibanez. The guitars that his company produces are similar in shape to the Ibanez Abasi prototype that Tosin unveiled in late 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://geargods.net/news/tosin-abasi-new-signature-guitar-prototype-is-bonkers/|title=TOSIN ABASI New Signature Guitar Prototype Is Bonkers - GearGods|date=2015-11-09|work=GearGods|access-date=2018-12-04|language=en-US}}</ref> These models can either be ordered as an 8-string or 6-string guitar. Abasi guitars has also unveiled the Pathos guitar pedal, which is a distortion pedal influenced by Abasi's sound.\n\n==Influences==\nHis favoured guitarists, musicians and bands include [[Steve Vai]], [[Allan Holdsworth]], [[Fredrik Thordendal]] of [[Meshuggah]], [[Thom Yorke]] of [[Radiohead]], [[Aphex Twin]], [[Squarepusher]], [[Mike Einziger]] of [[Incubus (band)|Incubus]], and [[Dream Theater]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/animals-as-leaders-tosin-abasi-10-essential-guitar-albums-597165|title=Animals As Leaders' Tosin Abasi: 10 essential guitar albums|publisher=Musicradar.com|accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref>[[File:TosinAbasi.jpg|thumb|300px|Tosin Abasi playing a .Strandberg* Headless 8-string]]\n\nHe is a [[Transcendental Meditation technique|Transcendental Meditation]] practitioner.<ref>{{cite web |first=Amy |last=Sciaretto |title=Animals as Leaders Guitarist Practices Transcendental Meditation |publisher=Noisecreep/AOL |date=April 12, 2010 |url=http://www.noisecreep.com/2010/04/12/animals-as-leaders-guitarist-practices-transcendental-meditation |accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===PSI (Pounds Per Square Inch)===\n*''Virus'' (2001)\n\n===Reflux===\n*''Illusion of Democracy'' (2004)\n\n===Animals as Leaders===\n*''[[Animals as Leaders (album)|Animals as Leaders]]'' (2009)\n*\"Wave of Babies (Digital Single)\" (2010)\n*''[[Weightless (Animals as Leaders album)|Weightless]]'' (2011)\n*''[[The Joy of Motion]]'' (2014)\n*''Animals as Leaders Encore Edition'' (2015)\n*''[[The Madness of Many]]'' (2016)\n\n===T.R.A.M.===\n*''Lingua Franca'' (Sumerian, 2012)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Animals as Leaders}}\n{{Born of Osiris}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Abasi, Tosin}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:African-American guitarists]]\n[[Category:African-American rock musicians]]\n[[Category:American people of Nigerian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Yoruba descent]]\n[[Category:Eight-string guitarists]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Lead guitarists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Progressive metal guitarists]]\n[[Category:Transcendental Meditation practitioners]]\n[[Category:Yoruba musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:Animals as Leaders members]]\n[[Category:Generation Axe members]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Nigerian American musician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Tosin Abasi\n| image               = File:Animals As Leaders @ Euroblast 2016 63.jpg\n| alt                 =\n| caption             = Tosin Abasi performing at the [[Euroblast Festival]] in Cologne, 2016\n| image_size          =\n| landscape           = yes\n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name          =\n| alias               =\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1983|01|07}}<br />[[Washington, D.C.]]\n| instrument          = Guitar, bass\n| genre               = [[Progressive metal]], [[metalcore]], [[djent]], [[instrumental rock]]<ref name=\"WCP\"/>\n| occupation          = Musician, songwriter\n| years_active        = 2000\u2013present\n| label               = [[Prosthetic Records|Prosthetic]], [[Sumerian Records|Sumerian]]\n| associated_acts     = [[Animals as Leaders]], Reflux, [[Born of Osiris]], [[Darkest Hour (band)|Darkest Hour]], T.R.A.M., PSI, Modern Day Babylon, Pomegranate Tiger, [[Generation Axe]]\n| website             = {{url|https://www.facebook.com/animalsasleaders|facebook.com/animalsasleaders}}\n}}\n\n'''Oluwatosin Ayoyinka Olumide''' \"'''Tosin'''\" '''Abasi''' (born January 7, 1983), is a [[Nigerian Americans|Nigerian American]] [[musician]], best known as the founder and lead [[guitarist]] of the [[instrumental]] [[progressive metal]] band [[Animals as Leaders]]. Before founding Animals as Leaders, he was the guitarist for the technical metalcore band Reflux.<ref name=\"WCP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/blogs/artsdesk/music/2009/02/09/qa-animals-as-leaders/|last=Allyn|first=Bobby|title=Q&A: Animals as Leaders|work=[[Washington City Paper]]|accessdate=2010-11-25}}</ref> He has recorded and released four albums with Animals as Leaders: a [[Animals as Leaders (album)|self-titled debut]], ''[[Weightless (Animals as Leaders album)|Weightless]]'', ''[[The Joy of Motion]]'' and their most recent album, ''[[The Madness of Many]]''. A guitar virtuoso, Guitar World ranks Abasi at #97 on their list of 100 Greatest Guitarists of all time.\n\n==Life and career==\n\n===Background===\nBorn in Washington D.C. to Nigerian immigrants to the United States,<ref name=\"noisecreep.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://noisecreep.com/animals-as-leaders-tosin-abasi-first-generation-american/ | title=Animals as leaders Tosin Abasi First Generation American}}</ref> Abasi's first name \"Oluwatosin\" means \"God is worthy to be served\" in [[Yoruba language|Yoruba]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourbabynamer.com/meaning-of-Oluwatosin.html|title=Oluwatosin|website=Baby Namer|accessdate=December 13, 2014}}</ref> His brother, Abdul Abasi, is a former drill sergeant in the [[United States military]] and is currently a fashion designer.\n\nAbasi is a mainly self-taught guitarist. He first picked up a guitar at his friend's house, simply strumming it and making up basic [[Lick (music)|licks]] on the spot. At this time he was being exposed to some music through learning the clarinet in elementary school. He later began to rent [[Glam metal|hair metal]] guitarists' instructional video tapes from his local music store, saying that some \"were videos you did not want to be caught watching\" due to racy material in certain tapes (e.g. women in bikinis).<ref name=\"YouTube\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZMv8739BtiA|title=Guitar Power ep. 1 featuring Tosin Abasi|work=YouTube|accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAbasi said that when he decided to learn the guitar, his father was \"totally liberal about the whole thing and encouraging and proud\" and in fact, bought him his first guitar. However his mother initially held a more conservative outlook. Tosin said in an interview, \u201cMy mom definitely represents more of the traditional immigrant mentality of education and conventional channels being way more important than a creative endeavor\".<ref name=\"noisecreep.com\"/>\n\n===Early career===\nHe was the guitarist for the Silver Spring, Maryland-based metal band PSI. He joined Reflux in the early to mid-2000s.  During a Reflux show, [[Prosthetic Records]] noticed his skill and offered him a record deal as a solo artist. At first, he refused, saying he didn't feel comfortable with his skill level to write his own record.<ref name=WCP/> Afterwards, Abasi enrolled at the Atlanta Institute of Music. After graduating, he contacted Prosthetic Records asking if the offer still held.<ref name=\"GEdge\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.guitaredge.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=509:tosin-abasi-8-string-animal&catid=45:interviews&Itemid=66 |title=Tosin Abasi: 8-String Animal |work=Guitar Edge |first=Elliott |last=Politte |accessdate=2010-12-17}}</ref> He then formed his \"solo\" project, [[Animals as Leaders]], the name loosely being derived from the book ''[[Ishmael (novel)|Ishmael]]''.<ref name=\"WCP\"/>\n\n===Success with Animals as Leaders and onward===\nIn 2009, he recorded the first Animals as Leaders release with [[Misha Mansoor]] (of [[Periphery (band)|Periphery]]), who produced and recorded the album with Tosin, as well as programming the drums. Javier Reyes and [[Navene Koperweis]] were enlisted on rhythm guitar and drums, respectively, after the completion of the album, turning the project into a full touring band.<ref name=\"GEdge\"/> He also toured with the band [[Born of Osiris]] as a stand-in guitarist for former member Matt Pantelis whilst they were auditioning for a permanent replacement.\n\nIn 2011, Tosin started putting together material for a new band, T.R.A.M., consisting of his Animals As Leaders bandmate Javier Reyes, Suicidal Tendencies drummer Eric Moore, and former [[The Mars Volta]] wind instrumentalist [[Adri\u00e1n Terrazas-Gonz\u00e1lez]]. \"T.R.A.M.\" stands for Terrazas, Reyes, Abasi, Moore. In mid-March 2011, T.R.A.M. played their first show at [[Sxsw|South by Southwest]], a multi-day music festival in Austin, Texas. Tosin explained that he formed T.R.A.M. as a trio consisting of himself, Javier and Adrian as an outlet for some ideas he had written which he felt did not fit with Animals as Leaders. Eric Moore was not added into the line-up until the recording phase of the album, and wrote and performed all the drums on the album within a few weeks.\n\nAnimals as Leaders released their second album, entitled \"Weightless\", on November 8, 2011.  Abasi was reportedly meeting with [[Misha Mansoor]] again in late 2012, and it was reported that a new Animals as Leaders album was in the works, due to be released in 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.guitarworld.com/peripherys-misha-mansoor-working-new-animals-leaders-album |title=Periphery's Misha Mansoor Working on New Animals as Leaders Album |accessdate=2013-02-19}}</ref>\n\nAt NAMM 2013, Tosin Abasi's signature guitar, the Ibanez TAM 100, was revealed. This guitar is based upon the [[Ibanez RG2228]] model, which he had been using for some years, and contains his signature [[DiMarzio]] Ionizer pickups.\n\nOn March 19, 2014, the [[Animals As Leaders]]' album ''[[The Joy of Motion]]'' was made available for streaming, via YouTube. On March 24, 2014, the album was released in Europe, March 25 in North America and on March 28 in Australia and New Zealand by Sumerian Records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalsucks.net/2014/03/19/stream-new-animals-leaders-album-joy-motion-right-now/|title=Stream the New Animals as Leaders Album The Joy of Motion Right Now!|work=MetalSucks|accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref> The album was met with widely positive reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/animals-as-leaders-the-joy-of-motion-review-596556|title=Animals As Leaders - The Joy Of Motion review|author=Chris Bird (Total Guitar)|publisher=Musicradar.com|accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/61502/Animals-as-Leaders-The-Joy-of-Motion/|title=Review: Animals As Leaders - The Joy of Motion - Sputnikmusic|publisher=Sputnikmusic.com|accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref> In July 2014, Tosin appeared in the first episode of Guitar Power, a web-series sponsored by D'Addario String and Rolling Stone Magazine.<ref name=\"YouTube\"/>\n\nAs of March 2014, he was on tour with Animals As Leaders. In October 2014, it was revealed that Abasi would join [[Joe Satriani]], [[Guthrie Govan]], and [[Mike Keneally]] on the [[G3 (tour)|G4 tour]] in 2015.<ref name=\"G3\">{{cite magazine | url=http://www.guitarworld.com/joe-satriani-announces-2015-g4-experience-featuring-guthrie-govan-tosin-abasi-mike-keneally-and-more-video | title=Joe Satriani Announces 2015 G4 Experience Featuring Guthrie Govan, Tosin Abasi, Mike Keneally and More \u2014 Video | magazine=[[Guitar World]] | date=October 28, 2014 | accessdate=January 12, 2015 | author=Fanelli, Damian}}</ref>\n\nIn April and May 2016, Abasi joined [[Nuno Bettencourt]], [[Yngwie Malmsteen]], [[Steve Vai]], and [[Zakk Wylde]], as part of the [[Generation Axe]] tour.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://generationaxe.com/| title=Generation Axe| accessdate=April 5, 2016}}</ref> The supergroup later reprised their tour in 2017 in Asia, and North America once more in 2018.\n\nTosin Abasi has started his own guitar brand, [https://abasiguitars.com/ Abasi Guitars], which opened in 2017,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.guitarworld.com/gear/tosin-abasi-launches-abasi-guitars-usa-falbo-animals-as-leaders-extended-range|title=Tosin Abasi Opens Up About Abasi Guitars, Names Key Personnel and More|work=guitarworld|access-date=2018-12-04|language=en}}</ref> after leaving Ibanez. The guitars that his company produces are similar in shape to the Ibanez Abasi prototype that Tosin unveiled in late 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://geargods.net/news/tosin-abasi-new-signature-guitar-prototype-is-bonkers/|title=TOSIN ABASI New Signature Guitar Prototype Is Bonkers - GearGods|date=2015-11-09|work=GearGods|access-date=2018-12-04|language=en-US}}</ref> These models can either be ordered as an 8-string or 6-string guitar. Abasi guitars has also unveiled the Pathos guitar pedal, which is a distortion pedal influenced by Abasi's sound.\n\n==Influences==\nHis favoured guitarists, musicians and bands include [[Steve Vai]], [[Allan Holdsworth]], [[Fredrik Thordendal]] of [[Meshuggah]], [[Thom Yorke]] of [[Radiohead]], [[Aphex Twin]], [[Squarepusher]], [[Mike Einziger]] of [[Incubus (band)|Incubus]], and [[Dream Theater]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/animals-as-leaders-tosin-abasi-10-essential-guitar-albums-597165|title=Animals As Leaders' Tosin Abasi: 10 essential guitar albums|publisher=Musicradar.com|accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref>[[File:TosinAbasi.jpg|thumb|300px|Tosin Abasi playing a .Strandberg* Headless 8-string]]\n\nHe is a [[Transcendental Meditation technique|Transcendental Meditation]] practitioner.<ref>{{cite web |first=Amy |last=Sciaretto |title=Animals as Leaders Guitarist Practices Transcendental Meditation |publisher=Noisecreep/AOL |date=April 12, 2010 |url=http://www.noisecreep.com/2010/04/12/animals-as-leaders-guitarist-practices-transcendental-meditation |accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===PSI (Pounds Per Square Inch)===\n*''Virus'' (2001)\n\n===Reflux===\n*''Illusion of Democracy'' (2004)\n\n===Animals as Leaders===\n*''[[Animals as Leaders (album)|Animals as Leaders]]'' (2009)\n*\"Wave of Babies (Digital Single)\" (2010)\n*''[[Weightless (Animals as Leaders album)|Weightless]]'' (2011)\n*''[[The Joy of Motion]]'' (2014)\n*''Animals as Leaders Encore Edition'' (2015)\n*''[[The Madness of Many]]'' (2016)\n\n===T.R.A.M.===\n*''Lingua Franca'' (Sumerian, 2012)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Animals as Leaders}}\n{{Born of Osiris}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Abasi, Tosin}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:African-American guitarists]]\n[[Category:African-American rock musicians]]\n[[Category:American people of Nigerian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Yoruba descent]]\n[[Category:Eight-string guitarists]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Lead guitarists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Progressive metal guitarists]]\n[[Category:Transcendental Meditation practitioners]]\n[[Category:Yoruba musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:Animals as Leaders members]]\n[[Category:Generation Axe members]]\n", "name_user": "109.78.42.124", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tosin_Abasi"}
{"title_page": "D.C.\u2013Dulles Line", "text_new": "\n\n{{Infobox bus line\n|box_width     = 300px\n|number        = 5A\n|logo          = <!-- bus logo (ex: Image_name.png) -->\n|logo_width    = <!-- width of bus logo -->\n|logo_alt      = <!-- logo image alternate text (only works if logo_width is supplied) -->\n|bgcolor       = <!-- background color for infobox title (hex codes need a '#', i.e. #00ff33 not 00ff33) -->\n|titlecolor    = <!-- color of the title text (hex codes need a '#') -->\n|subheader     = D.C.\u2013Dulles Line\n|operatorlogo  = WMATA Metrobus logo.svg\n|oplogo_width  = 250px\n|image         = WMATA Metrobus 5A at Rosslyn.jpg\n|image_width   = 300px\n|image_alt     = <!-- This image cannot be displayed. -->\n|caption       = Route 5A at [[Rosslyn station]] in 2012.\n|system        = [[Metrobus (Washington, D.C.)|Metrobus]]\n|operator      = [[Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority]]\n|garage        = Four Mile Run\n|livery        =\n|pvr           =\n|status        = In Service\n|open          = December 4, 2000<ref name=\"December2000\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wmata.com/metrobus/5ABROC1.PDF |title=NEW Direct 5A DC-Dulles Line |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010702094940/http://www.wmata.com/metrobus/5ABROC1.PDF |archive-date=July 2, 2001 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|close         = est. September 2020 or 2021<ref name=\"Opening\">{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Max |date=August 5, 2019 |title=Metro's Silver Line extension to Dulles gets tentative opening date |url=https://www.insidenova.com/news/regional/metro-s-silver-line-to-dulles-gets-tentative-opening-date/article_d27f626c-b7f0-11e9-a1eb-93b797b05cdc.html |newspaper=InsideNova |accessdate=August 16, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"sept2020\">{{cite web |last1=Pascale |first1=Jordan |title=The Silver Line\u2019s Second Phase Is Looking At A Potential September Opening Date |url=https://dcist.com/story/19/11/25/the-silver-lines-second-phase-is-looking-at-a-potential-september-opening-date/ |website=DCist |accessdate=11 December 2019 |date=25 November 2019}}</ref>\n|predecessors  =\n|night         =\n|locale        = [[Loudoun County, Virginia|Loudoun County]]<br>[[Fairfax County, Virginia|Fairfax County]]<br>[[Arlington County, Virginia|Arlington County]]<br>[[Southwest (Washington, D.C.)]]\n|communities   = [[Dulles, Virginia|Dulles]]<br>[[Herndon, Virginia|Herndon]]<br>[[Rosslyn, Virginia|Rosslyn]]<br>[[Southwest (Washington, D.C.)]]\n|landmarks     = [[Washington Dulles International Airport]]<br>[[Rosslyn station]]<br>[[L'Enfant Plaza station]]\n|termini       = <!-- used when route starts and stops at a single location, overrides the start and end parameters -->\n|start         = [[L'Enfant Plaza station]]\n|via           = [[Virginia State Route 267|Dulles Toll Road]]<br>[[Interstate 66|Custis Memorial Parkway (I-66)]]<br>[[Virginia State Route 110|Richmond Highway]]<br>[[Interstate 395 (Virginia\u2013District of Columbia)|Interstate 395]]\n|end           =  [[Washington Dulles International Airport]]\n|length        = \n|otherroutes   =\n|compete       =\n|ibus          =\n|level         = Daily\n|level1        =\n|frequency     = 30-35 minutes (weekdays)<br>60 minutes (weekends)\n|alt_frequency = \n|time          =\n|day           = 4:50 AM \u2013 12:17 AM (weekdays)<br>5:30 AM \u2013 12:18 AM (Saturdays)<br>5:30 AM \u2013 12:10 AM (Sundays)\n|zone          =\n|timetable_link= [https://wmata.com/schedules/timetables/upload/5A_170625.pdf D.C.\u2013Dulles Line]\n|ridership     =\n|fare          = $7.50\n|cash          = Exact change required\n|transfers     = [[SmarTrip]] only\n|map_link      = <!-- external link to an online map (ex: [http://www.example.com/map.html Line xx map]) -->\n|map           = {{D.C.\u2013Dulles Line|inline=yes}}\n|map_state     = collapsed\n|map_name      = <!-- name of the map (defaults to 'Route map') -->\n|previous_line = [[Pershing Drive\u2013Arlington Boulevard Line|4B]]\n|next_line     = [[Lincolnia\u2013North Fairlington Line|7A]]\n|notes         = <!-- anything special in small font, centered at the bottom of the infobox -->\n}}\n\nThe '''D.C.\u2013Dulles Line''', designated '''Route 5A''', is a bus route operated by the [[Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority]] between [[Washington Dulles International Airport]] and the [[L'Enfant Plaza station|L'Enfant Plaza Metro Station]] of the [[Blue Line (WMATA)|Blue]], [[Yellow Line (WMATA)|Yellow]], [[Orange Line (WMATA)|Orange]], [[Green Line (WMATA)|Green]], and [[Silver Line (WMATA)|Silver]] lines of the [[Metrorail (Washington)|Washington Metro]]. The line operates every 30-35 minutes on weekdays, and 60 minutes on weekends along the [[Virginia State Route 267|Dulles Toll Road]], [[Interstate 66]], [[Virginia State Route 110|Richmond Highway]], and [[Interstate 395 (Virginia\u2013District of Columbia)|Interstate 395]] between these two locations with no intermediate stops, with the exception of the Herndon\u2013Monroe Park and Ride and [[Rosslyn station]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Transportation between Washington, D.C. and Dulles Airport |url=https://freetoursbyfoot.com/transportation-washington-d-c-dulles-airport/|accessdate=24 November 2019}}</ref> The trip is approximately 50 minutes long.\n\n==Service==\nService operates every 30 to 35 minutes between [[L'Enfant Plaza station]] and [[Washington Dulles International Airport]] on weekdays, and 60 minutes on weekends.<ref name=\"Transportation\">https://www.flydulles.com/iad/other-transportation-options</ref> WMATA uses some 2006 Orion VII CNG (07.501) suburbans numbered 2701-2730 to operate on the route based out of Four Mile Run Division. However, other buses can be used on the route if the Orion VII CNGs are running on other routes or going under maintenance. Each bus has suburban seating with overhead luggage racks. As the [[Silver Line (WMATA)|Silver Line]] of the Washington Metro is expected to open at [[Dulles International Airport station]] between 2020 and 2021, the route uses regular transit buses.<ref name=\"sept2020\"/>\n\n==Background==\nThe 5A originally operated under the \u201cNorth Reston Express Line\u201d back in the 1970s before being discontinued in the 1990s being replaced by a combination of [[Fairfax Connector]] routes.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1983/06/15/metrobus-routes-to-change-june-26/04a83f34-9b5e-4917-8cb0-6b16fc5d0fe1/</ref>\n\nService began in December 4, 2000 to connect service to Dulles International Airport from Downtown Washington D.C.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ggwash.org/view/31752/dc-fairfax-consider-cutting-the-5a-bus-to-dulles |title=DC, Fairfax consider cutting the 5A bus to Dulles |date=July 10, 2013|website=ggwash.org||last1=Alpert|first1=David|access-date=November 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe line is unique for being the only WMATA bus line that runs to [[Loudoun County, Virginia|Loudoun County]], and has a connection with any Virginia non-commuter services, and is responsible for providing a regular link between the two services. The original $1.10 one-way fare was seen as a bargain compared with other transportation modes in the area, including [[Shenandoah Valley Commuter Bus]].<ref name=\"Transportation\"/>\n\nIn 2014, it was reported that the 5A line was partly responsible for Dulles Airport monthly ridership record.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wmata.com/pdfs/planning/2014-05%20Bus%20Ridership.pdf |title=Metrobus Monthly Ridership Bus Line, Sector and Jurisdictional Summary May 2014 - Preliminary |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121010532/https://www.wmata.com/pdfs/planning/2014-05%20Bus%20Ridership.pdf |archive-date=January 21, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> WMATA also provides higher levels of service on the line in special times of need, especially on certain holidays.<ref>{{cite press release|agency=WMATA|url=https://www.wmata.com/about/news/pressreleasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=4740|title=Metro to have additional buses and trains on standby in anticipation of Thanksgiving week travel to regional airports|date=November 17, 2010|accessdate=March 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Silver Line==\n\n{{Main||Silver Line (Washington Metro)}}\n\nIn 2010, WMATA started a public planning forum, to create the Silver Line route to run to Dulles Airport.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/07/18/AR2010071802729.html |title=Development near Herndon's future Metro station topic of public forum Monday |last=Hosh |first=Kafia A. |date=July 19, 2010 |access-date=November 9, 2010 |publisher=Washington Post}}</ref> The Silver Line will bring riders access via train to serve in Maryland, Washington D.C., and the northeastern portion of Virginia. This project is under Phase 2 of the Silver Line, as Phase 1 runs up to [[Wiehle\u2013Reston East station]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/all-aboard-metros-new-silver-line-rolls-down-the-tracks-for-the-first-time/2014/07/26/238aaa68-14cc-11e4-8936-26932bcfd6ed_story.html |title=All aboard! Metro's new Silver Line rolls down the tracks for the first time. |website=Washington Post |access-date=May 28, 2018}}</ref> Construction of Phase 2 started in 2014, and is scheduled to open in 2020.<ref name=\"delayed\">{{Cite news |url=http://wamu.org/news/15/04/27/second_phase_of_silver_line_delayed_by_at_least_13_months |title=Second Phase Of Silver Line Delayed By At Least 13 Months |last=Di Caro |first=Martin |date=April 27, 2015 |access-date=April 27, 2015 |website=WAMU}}</ref> Metro officials then announced that the second phase may not be ready for service until about September 2020.<ref name=\"sept2020\"/> \n\n===Dulles Airport station===\n\n{{Main||Dulles International Airport station}}\n\nThe Washington Dulles International Airport is expected to serve on its own train station, as the station is part of Phase 2 of the Silver Line. The station was originally planned to be underground,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dullesmetro.com/silver-line-stations/dulles-airport/ |title=Dulles Metro: Dulles Station |accessdate=2014-12-05}}</ref> but the plans call for an above-ground station, which will be located next to daily parking garage 1 of the airport.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sherfinski |first=David |date=July 20, 2011 |title=Airports board approves above-ground Dulles Metro station |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2011/jul/20/mwaa-approves-plan-above-ground-dulles-metrorail-s/ |newspaper=[[The Washington Times]] |accessdate=2014-12-06 }}</ref> The station will be connected to the terminal building using the existing pedestrian tunnel which connects the hourly and daily parking lots and parking garage 1 to the baggage claim level of the airport terminal, and which is equipped with [[moving walkway|moving sidewalks]]. The Dulles International Airport station is scheduled to open between 2020 and 2021, and expected to replace the 5A.<ref name=\"Opening\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/dr-gridlock/wp/2015/09/03/why-metro-wants-to-kill-the-dulles-bus-route/ |title=Why Metro wants to kill the Dulles 5A bus route |website=Washington Post |access-date=November 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>https://wamu.org/story/19/11/22/silver-line-extension-could-maybe-possibly-open-in-september/</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Greenbelt\u2013BWI Thurgood Marshall Airport Express Line]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.wmata.com/bus/ Metrobus]\n\n{{Airports in the Baltimore-Washington area}}\n{{Major US Airports}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:D.C.-Dulles Line}}\n[[Category:Metrobus (Washington, D.C.) routes|5A]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Washington Dulles International Airport]]\n[[Category:Loudoun County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Fairfax County, Virginia]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{Infobox bus line\n|box_width     = 300px\n|number        = 5A\n|logo          = <!-- bus logo (ex: Image_name.png) -->\n|logo_width    = <!--