unty, Virginia|Fairfax County]]<br>[[Arlington County, Virginia|Arlington County]]<br>[[Southwest (Washington, D.C.)]]\n|communities   = [[Dulles, Virginia|Dulles]]<br>[[Herndon, Virginia|Herndon]]<br>[[Arlington County, Virginia|Arlington County]]<br>[[Southwest (Washington, D.C.)]]\n|landmarks     = [[Washington Dulles International Airport]]<br>[[Rosslyn station]]<br>[[L'Enfant Plaza station]]\n|termini       = <!-- used when route starts and stops at a single location, overrides the start and end parameters -->\n|start         = [[L'Enfant Plaza station]]\n|via           = [[Virginia State Route 267|Dulles Toll Road]]<br>[[Interstate 66|Custis Memorial Parkway (I-66)]]<br>[[Virginia State Route 110|Richmond Highway]]<br>[[Interstate 395 (Virginia\u2013District of Columbia)|Interstate 395]]\n|end           =  [[Washington Dulles International Airport]]\n|length        = \n|otherroutes   =\n|compete       =\n|ibus          =\n|level         = Daily\n|level1        =\n|frequency     = 30-35 minutes (weekdays)<br>60 minutes (weekends)\n|alt_frequency = \n|time          =\n|day           = 4:50 AM \u2013 12:17 AM (weekdays)<br>5:30 AM \u2013 12:18 AM (Saturdays)<br>5:30 AM \u2013 12:10 AM (Sundays)\n|zone          =\n|timetable_link= [https://wmata.com/schedules/timetables/upload/5A_170625.pdf D.C.\u2013Dulles Line]\n|ridership     =\n|fare          = $7.50\n|cash          = Exact change required\n|transfers     = [[SmarTrip]] only\n|map_link      = <!-- external link to an online map (ex: [http://www.example.com/map.html Line xx map]) -->\n|map           = {{D.C.\u2013Dulles Line|inline=yes}}\n|map_state     = collapsed\n|map_name      = <!-- name of the map (defaults to 'Route map') -->\n|previous_line = [[Pershing Drive\u2013Arlington Boulevard Line|4B]]\n|next_line     = [[Lincolnia\u2013North Fairlington Line|7A]]\n|notes         = <!-- anything special in small font, centered at the bottom of the infobox -->\n}}\n\nThe '''D.C.\u2013Dulles Line''', designated '''Route 5A''', is a bus route operated by the [[Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority]] between [[Washington Dulles International Airport]] and the [[L'Enfant Plaza station|L'Enfant Plaza Metro Station]] of the [[Blue Line (WMATA)|Blue]], [[Yellow Line (WMATA)|Yellow]], [[Orange Line (WMATA)|Orange]], [[Green Line (WMATA)|Green]], and [[Silver Line (WMATA)|Silver]] lines of the [[Metrorail (Washington)|Washington Metro]]. The line operates every 30-35 minutes on weekdays, and 60 minutes on weekends along the [[Virginia State Route 267|Dulles Toll Road]], [[Interstate 66]], [[Virginia State Route 110|Richmond Highway]], and [[Interstate 395 (Virginia\u2013District of Columbia)|Interstate 395]] between these two locations with no intermediate stops, with the exception of the Herndon\u2013Monroe Park and Ride and [[Rosslyn station]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Transportation between Washington, D.C. and Dulles Airport |url=https://freetoursbyfoot.com/transportation-washington-d-c-dulles-airport/|accessdate=24 November 2019}}</ref> The trip is approximately 50 minutes long.\n\n==Service==\nService operates every 30 to 35 minutes between [[L'Enfant Plaza station]] and [[Washington Dulles International Airport]] on weekdays, and 60 minutes on weekends.<ref name=\"Transportation\">https://www.flydulles.com/iad/other-transportation-options</ref> WMATA uses some 2006 Orion VII CNG (07.501) suburbans numbered 2701-2730 to operate on the route based out of Four Mile Run Division. However, other buses can be used on the route if the Orion VII CNGs are running on other routes or going under maintenance. Each bus has suburban seating with overhead luggage racks. As the [[Silver Line (WMATA)|Silver Line]] of the Washington Metro is expected to open at [[Dulles International Airport station]] between 2020 and 2021, the route uses regular transit buses.<ref name=\"sept2020\"/>\n\n==Background==\nThe 5A originally operated under the \u201cNorth Reston Express Line\u201d back in the 1970s before being discontinued in the 1990s being replaced by a combination of [[Fairfax Connector]] routes.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1983/06/15/metrobus-routes-to-change-june-26/04a83f34-9b5e-4917-8cb0-6b16fc5d0fe1/</ref>\n\nService began in December 4, 2000 to connect service to Dulles International Airport from Downtown Washington D.C.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ggwash.org/view/31752/dc-fairfax-consider-cutting-the-5a-bus-to-dulles |title=DC, Fairfax consider cutting the 5A bus to Dulles |date=July 10, 2013|website=ggwash.org||last1=Alpert|first1=David|access-date=November 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe line is unique for being the only WMATA bus line that runs to [[Loudoun County, Virginia|Loudoun County]], and has a connection with any Virginia non-commuter services, and is responsible for providing a regular link between the two services. The original $1.10 one-way fare was seen as a bargain compared with other transportation modes in the area, including [[Shenandoah Valley Commuter Bus]].<ref name=\"Transportation\"/>\n\nIn 2014, it was reported that the 5A line was partly responsible for Dulles Airport monthly ridership record.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wmata.com/pdfs/planning/2014-05%20Bus%20Ridership.pdf |title=Metrobus Monthly Ridership Bus Line, Sector and Jurisdictional Summary May 2014 - Preliminary |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121010532/https://www.wmata.com/pdfs/planning/2014-05%20Bus%20Ridership.pdf |archive-date=January 21, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> WMATA also provides higher levels of service on the line in special times of need, especially on certain holidays.<ref>{{cite press release|agency=WMATA|url=https://www.wmata.com/about/news/pressreleasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=4740|title=Metro to have additional buses and trains on standby in anticipation of Thanksgiving week travel to regional airports|date=November 17, 2010|accessdate=March 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Silver Line==\n\n{{Main||Silver Line (Washington Metro)}}\n\nIn 2010, WMATA started a public planning forum, to create the Silver Line route to run to Dulles Airport.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/07/18/AR2010071802729.html |title=Development near Herndon's future Metro station topic of public forum Monday |last=Hosh |first=Kafia A. |date=July 19, 2010 |access-date=November 9, 2010 |publisher=Washington Post}}</ref> The Silver Line will bring riders access via train to serve in Maryland, Washington D.C., and the northeastern portion of Virginia. This project is under Phase 2 of the Silver Line, as Phase 1 runs up to [[Wiehle\u2013Reston East station]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/all-aboard-metros-new-silver-line-rolls-down-the-tracks-for-the-first-time/2014/07/26/238aaa68-14cc-11e4-8936-26932bcfd6ed_story.html |title=All aboard! Metro's new Silver Line rolls down the tracks for the first time. |website=Washington Post |access-date=May 28, 2018}}</ref> Construction of Phase 2 started in 2014, and is scheduled to open in 2020.<ref name=\"delayed\">{{Cite news |url=http://wamu.org/news/15/04/27/second_phase_of_silver_line_delayed_by_at_least_13_months |title=Second Phase Of Silver Line Delayed By At Least 13 Months |last=Di Caro |first=Martin |date=April 27, 2015 |access-date=April 27, 2015 |website=WAMU}}</ref> Metro officials then announced that the second phase may not be ready for service until about September 2020.<ref name=\"sept2020\"/> \n\n===Dulles Airport station===\n\n{{Main||Dulles International Airport station}}\n\nThe Washington Dulles International Airport is expected to serve on its own train station, as the station is part of Phase 2 of the Silver Line. The station was originally planned to be underground,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dullesmetro.com/silver-line-stations/dulles-airport/ |title=Dulles Metro: Dulles Station |accessdate=2014-12-05}}</ref> but the plans call for an above-ground station, which will be located next to daily parking garage 1 of the airport.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sherfinski |first=David |date=July 20, 2011 |title=Airports board approves above-ground Dulles Metro station |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2011/jul/20/mwaa-approves-plan-above-ground-dulles-metrorail-s/ |newspaper=[[The Washington Times]] |accessdate=2014-12-06 }}</ref> The station will be connected to the terminal building using the existing pedestrian tunnel which connects the hourly and daily parking lots and parking garage 1 to the baggage claim level of the airport terminal, and which is equipped with [[moving walkway|moving sidewalks]]. The Dulles International Airport station is scheduled to open between 2020 and 2021, and expected to replace the 5A.<ref name=\"Opening\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/dr-gridlock/wp/2015/09/03/why-metro-wants-to-kill-the-dulles-bus-route/ |title=Why Metro wants to kill the Dulles 5A bus route |website=Washington Post |access-date=November 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>https://wamu.org/story/19/11/22/silver-line-extension-could-maybe-possibly-open-in-september/</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Greenbelt\u2013BWI Thurgood Marshall Airport Express Line]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.wmata.com/bus/ Metrobus]\n\n{{Airports in the Baltimore-Washington area}}\n{{Major US Airports}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:D.C.-Dulles Line}}\n[[Category:Metrobus (Washington, D.C.) routes|5A]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Washington Dulles International Airport]]\n[[Category:Loudoun County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Fairfax County, Virginia]]\n", "name_user": "Leobran2018", "label": "safe", "comment": "Corrected community served.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D.C.%E2%80%93Dulles_Line"}
{"title_page": "Eugene Levy", "text_new": "{{For|the New York State Senator|Eugene Levy (politician)}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=February 2015}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Eugene Levy\n| honorific_suffix = [[Member of the Order of Canada|CM]]\n| image = Eugene Levy 2, 2012.jpg\n| caption = Levy in November 2012\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1946|12|17}}\n| birth_place = [[Hamilton, Ontario]], Canada\n| residence = {{ubl|[[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.|[[St. Augustine, Florida]], U.S.|<!--where in-->[[Canada]]}}\n| occupation = Actor, comedian, producer, director, writer\n| years_active = 1969\u2013present\n| spouse = {{marriage|Deborah Divine|1977}}\n| children = {{hlist|[[Dan Levy (Canadian actor)|Dan Levy]]|[[Sarah Levy]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Eugene Levy''', [[Member of the Order of Canada|CM]] (born December 17, 1946) is a Canadian actor, comedian, producer, director, and writer. He is the only actor to have appeared in all eight of the ''[[American Pie (film series)|American Pie]]'' films, in his role as [[List of American Pie characters#Noah Levenstein|Noah Levenstein]]. He often plays flustered and unconventional figures. He is a regular collaborator of actor-director [[Christopher Guest]], appearing in and co-writing four of his films, commencing with ''[[Waiting for Guffman]]'' (1996).\n\nLevy received the [[Governor General's Performing Arts Award]], Canada's highest honour in the performing arts, in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=Eugene Levy biography|url=http://ggpaa.ca/award-recipients/2008/levy-eugene.aspx|publisher=Governor General's Performing Arts Awards Foundation|accessdate=February 10, 2015}}</ref> He was appointed to the [[Order of Canada]] on June 30, 2011.<ref>[http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=14175&lan=eng \"Governor General Announces 50 New Appointments to the Order of Canada\"], June 30, 2011.</ref> He currently stars as [[Johnny Rose]] in ''[[Schitt's Creek]]'', a comedy series that he co-created with his son and co-star, [[Dan Levy (Canadian actor)|Dan Levy]]. In 2019, he was nominated for the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Comedy Series]].\n\n==Early life==\nLevy was born to a [[Jews|Jewish]] family<ref name=\"levy\">{{cite journal | last =Rosen | first =Steven | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =Want to spoof Purim and the Oscars? Be our Guest! | journal =The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles | volume =21 | issue =39 | pages = | publisher = | date =November 16, 2006 | url =http://www.jewishjournal.com/home/preview.php?id=16799 | doi = | id = | accessdate =November 16, 2006 }}</ref> in [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]], [[Ontario]]. His mother was a homemaker and his father was a foreman at an automobile plant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20140759,00.html|title=Ditz Hits|work=people.com}}</ref> He went to [[Westdale Secondary School]] and attended [[McMaster University]]. He was vice-president of the McMaster Film Board, a student film group, where he met moviemaker [[Ivan Reitman]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thespec.com/community-story/6868483-1960s-and-70s-mcmaster-produces-funnymen-short-levy-thomas-reitman-and-candy/|title=1960s and \u201970s: McMaster produces funnymen Short, Levy, Thomas, Reitman and Candy|date=2016-09-23|work=The Hamilton Spectator|access-date=2019-01-03|language=en-CA|issn=1189-9417}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Eugene Levy 2011.jpg|thumb|Eugene Levy 2011]]\nAn alumnus of both [[the Second City]], [[Toronto]] and the sketch comedy series ''[[Second City Television]]'', Levy often plays unusual supporting characters with nerdish streaks. Perhaps his best-known role on ''[[Second City Television|SCTV]]'' is the dimwitted [[Earl Camembert]], a news anchor for the \"SCTV News\" and a parody of real-life Canadian newsman [[Earl Cameron (broadcaster)|Earl Cameron]]. Celebrities impersonated by Levy on SCTV include [[Perry Como]], [[Ricardo Montalb\u00e1n]], [[Alex Trebek]], [[Sean Connery]], [[Howard Cosell]], [[Henry Kissinger]], [[Menachem Begin]], [[Bud Abbott]], [[Milton Berle]], [[John Charles Daly]], [[Gene Shalit]], [[Judd Hirsch]], [[Jack Carter (comedian)|Jack Carter]], [[Muammar al-Gaddafi]], [[Tony Dow]], [[James Caan (actor)|James Caan]], [[Lorne Greene]], [[Rex Reed]], Ralph Young (of [[Sandler and Young]]), [[F. Lee Bailey]], [[Ernest Borgnine]], former Ontario chief coroner and talk show host Dr. [[Morton Shulman]], [[Norman Mailer]], [[Neil Sedaka]] and [[Howard McNear]] as Floyd the Barber.\n\nOriginal Levy characterizations on ''SCTV'' are comic Bobby Bittman, scandal sheet entrepreneur Dr. Raoul Withers, \"report on business\" na\u00eff Brian Johns, 3-D horror auteur Woody Tobias Jr., cheerful Leutonian [[accordion]]ist Stan Schmenge, lecherous dream interpreter Raoul Wilson, hammer-voiced sports broadcaster Lou Jaffe, diminutive union patriarch Sid Dithers (\"San Francisckie! Did you drove or did you flew?\"), fey current-events commentator Joel Weiss, buttoned-down panel show moderator Dougal Currie, smarmy ''Just for Fun'' emcee Stan Kanter, energetic used car salesman Al Peck, guileless security guard Gus Gustofferson, Phil the Garment King (also of Phil's Nails), and the inept teen dance show host Rockin\u2019 Mel Slirrup.\n\nThough he has been the \"above the title\" star in only two films, ''[[Armed and Dangerous (1986 film)|Armed and Dangerous]]'' (1986) and ''[[The Man (2005 film)|The Man]]'' (2005), he has featured prominently in many films. He is the co-writer and frequent cast member of [[Christopher Guest]]\u2019s mockumentary features, particularly ''[[A Mighty Wind]]'', where his sympathetic performance as emotionally unstable folksinger Mitch Cohen won kudos; his accolades included a [[Satellite Award for Best Supporting Actor - Motion Picture|Satellite Award for Best Supporting Actor - Musical or Comedy]] and the prestigious [[New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Supporting Actor]]. In the 1980s and 1990s, he appeared in ''[[Splash (film)|Splash]]'', ''[[National Lampoon's Vacation|National Lampoon\u2019s Vacation]]'', ''[[Club Paradise]]'', ''[[Stay Tuned (film)|Stay Tuned]]'', ''[[Multiplicity (film)|Multiplicity]]'' and other comedies. Levy was the creator of ''[[Maniac Mansion (TV series)|Maniac Mansion]]'', a television sitcom based on the [[LucasArts]] [[Maniac Mansion (video game)|video game of the same name]]. He was also seriously considered for the role of [[Toby Ziegler]] on ''[[The West Wing]]'', a role that went to actor [[Richard Schiff]].\n\nLevy, along with his son [[Dan Levy (Canadian actor)|Dan Levy]], is co-creator of the [[CBC Television|CBC]]/[[Pop (American TV channel)|Pop TV]] sitcom, ''[[Schitt's Creek]]''. He also stars in the show alongside his son as head of the Rose family, Johnny Rose. His daughter, [[Sarah Levy]], portrays Twyla Sands, the waitress at the Schitt\u2018s Creek diner.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://deadline.com/2015/01/schitts-creek-eugene-levy-son-daniel-levy-tca-1201345586/|title=Eugene Levy & Son On \u2018Schitt\u2019s Creek\u2019: \"We\u2019ll Never Know Where The Town Is\" \u2013 TCA|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=2015-01-09|newspaper=Deadline|language=en-US|access-date=2016-12-02}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\nLevy, along with [[Christopher Guest]] and [[Michael McKean]], was awarded the 2003 [[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media|Best Song Written for a Motion Picture, Television, or Other Visual Media]] for the title song from ''A Mighty Wind''. Levy appeared in the corner of a poster hanging outside the movie theatre in Springfield in the \"[[See Homer Run]]\" episode of ''[[The Simpsons]]''. (The poster was advertising for ''Princess Rock Star'' and featured a girl with an [[electric guitar]], with Levy in the corner wearing a royal crown. A liner note under him read \"Eugene Levy as the King\").\n\nIn March 2006, it was announced that he would receive a star on [[Canada's Walk of Fame]]. In 2002, the entire cast of ''SCTV'' was given a group star, and although Levy is not mentioned on the actual star, he was still inducted as a part of the group. This makes him one of only four two-time honourees, alongside fellow ''SCTV'' alumni [[John Candy]], [[Martin Short]] and [[Catherine O'Hara]].\n\nLevy is one of only a handful of people who have won at least five [[Canadian Comedy Awards]], including two for Best Writing (''[[Best in Show (film)|Best in Show]]'' in 2001 and ''[[A Mighty Wind]]'' in 2004) and three for Best Male Performer (''Best in Show'', ''[[American Pie 2]]'' in 2002, and ''A Mighty Wind'').\n\nIn 2008, the [[Governor General of Canada]] presented Levy with the Governor General's Performing Arts Awards (GGPAA), a lifetime achievement award considered \"for their outstanding body of work and enduring contribution to the performing arts in Canada.\".<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://ggpaa.ca/award-recipients/2008/levy-eugene.aspx|title = Eugene Levy: 2008 Lifetime Artistic Achievement (Broadcasting)|accessdate=September 10, 2018}}</ref> In 2010, Levy was awarded the [[ACTRA Award]] by the [[ACTRA|union representing Canada's actors]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.news957.com/entertainment/article/17025--actra-to-give-eugene-levy-award-of-excellence-in-los-angeles |title=ACTRA to give Eugene Levy Award of Excellence in Los Angeles |accessdate=2012-05-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120905154018/http://www.news957.com/entertainment/article/17025--actra-to-give-eugene-levy-award-of-excellence-in-los-angeles |archivedate=September 5, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Levy was made a Member of the [[Order of Canada]] \"for his contributions as a comic actor and writer, and for his dedication to charitable causes.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=14175&lan=eng|title=Appointments to the Order of Canada|date=June 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn May 22, 2012, Levy delivered a commencement address at [[Dalhousie University]], in Halifax, Nova Scotia, and was awarded the degree Doctor of Laws (honoris causa).\n\nOn June 11, 2012, Levy was presented with the [[Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal]] by the Lieutenant Governor of Ontario.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/story/2012/06/18/jubilee-gala-toronto.html| title=Diamond Jubilee Gala toasts exceptional Canadians| date=June 18, 2012| publisher=CBC| accessdate=June 19, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, 2016, Levy took home the award for \"Best Performance by an Actor in a Continuing Leading Comedic Role\" at the 4th Annual [[Canadian Screen Awards]], for his performance as Johnny Rose in the [[CBC Television|CBC]]/[[Pop (American TV channel)|Pop TV]] sitcom, ''[[Schitt's Creek]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2016/03/14/canadian-screen-awards-2016_n_9456460.html|title=The Canadian Screen Awards: Call 'Em The 'Candys' From Now On|website=The Huffington Post|access-date=2016-12-02}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLevy married Deborah Divine in 1977. They live in [[Los Angeles]], [[St. Augustine, Florida]] and [[Canada]]<ref>[http://virtualglobetrotting.com/map/ted-danson-mary-steenburgens-house/view/google/ Eugene Levy's House in Los Angeles, CA (Google Maps) - Virtual Globetrotting] Retrieved December 17, 2017.</ref> and have two children together: actor [[Dan Levy (Canadian actor)|Dan]] and actress [[Sarah Levy|Sarah]], both of whom star alongside him on ''[[Schitt's Creek]]''.\n\nLevy is an advocate for [[autism]] awareness and treatment.<ref name=\"CTVNews.ca\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/eugene-levy-to-be-autism-treatment-spokesman-1.244693 |title=Eugene Levy to be autism treatment spokesman |date=June 12, 2007 |website=CTVNews.ca |publisher=[[CTV Television Network]] |access-date=December 18, 2016 |quote=}}</ref> He was a close friend of [[John Candy]], who died of a [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]] in 1994. Levy is a member of the Canadian charity Artists Against Racism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://artistsagainstracism.org/artists/|title=Artists - Artists Against Racism|website=artistsagainstracism.org}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class = \"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1971\n| ''[[Foxy Lady (film)|Foxy Lady]]''\n| Coffee Boy\n|\n|-\n| 1973\n| ''[[Cannibal Girls]]''\n| Clifford Sturges\n|\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[Running (film)|Running]]''\n| Richie Rosenberg\n|\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[Nothing Personal (1980 film)|Nothing Personal]]''\n| Marty\n|\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[Deadly Companion]]''\n| Matt\n|\n|-\n| 1981\n| ''[[Heavy Metal (film)|Heavy Metal]]''\n| [[Captain Sternn|Captain Lincoln F. Sternn]] / Male Reporter / Edsel\n| Voices\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''[[National Lampoon's Vacation|National Lampoon\u2019s Vacation]]''\n| Ed the Car Salesman\n|\n|-\n| 1983\n|  ''[[Going Berserk]]''\n| Sal DiPasquale\n|\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[Splash (film)|Splash]]''\n| Walter Kornbluth\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Club Paradise]]''\n| Barry Steinberg\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n|  ''[[Armed and Dangerous (1986 film)|Armed and Dangerous]]''\n| Norman Kane\n|\n|-\n| 1987\n|  ''[[Bride of Boogedy]]''\n| Tom Lynch\n|\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[Speed Zone]]''\n| Leo Ross\n|\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[Father of the Bride (1991 film)|Father of the Bride]]''\n| Singer at Audition\n|\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Once Upon A Crime|Once Upon a Crime]]''\n| Casino Cashier\n| Uncredited<br />Also director\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Stay Tuned (film)|Stay Tuned]]''\n| Crowley\n|\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''[[I Love Trouble (1994 film)|I Love Trouble]]''\n| Ray, Justice of the Peace\n|\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[Father of the Bride Part II]]''\n| Mr. Habib\n|\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Multiplicity (film)|Multiplicity]]''\n| Vic\n|\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Waiting for Guffman]]''\n| Dr. Allan Pearl\n| Also writer\n|-\n| 1998\n|''[[Almost Heroes]]''\n| Guy Fontenot\n|\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Holy Man]]''\n| Guy on Background T